INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0113','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0036','CONSUMED','MODERATE',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0037','CONSUMED','MODERATE',NULL,'controls-and-hardware',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0038','CLOSED','MODERATE',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas',NULL,NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0148','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','The cognitive-science BPC establishes "≤2 decision points visible simultaneously" as a cognitive load specification. The detectable-gradient-protocol specifies multi-sensory zone boundaries (LRV change, RT60 change, luminance change) at every transition. Zone boundary signals occurring at a wayfinding decision point ADD to information load — creating the maximum cognitive load condition (simultaneous navigation decision + sensory transition). For DEM/NEU/ABI: exceeds degraded executive function. For NDV/AUT: sensory overload at the moment requiring focused attention. For VIS: contrast changes at junctions may mask directional cues.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0149','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','Stair descent fall risk = 3× ascent (Simoneau 1991); 6mm riser irregularity = +18% misstep (Templer 1992). 30% LRV is a regulatory floor with no empirical basis; ~65% Michelson needed for reliable surface boundary detection (Dain/Manandhar 2022). Harper 2022 bridges both: combined step-face AND edge contrast enhancement reduced fall events (OR 2.87). The highest-risk built environment feature (stairs) has the weakest contrast specification (general 30% LRV). Stair nosings should carry a SEPARATE, HIGHER contrast specification.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0150','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','Kitchen BPC: ≥400mm prep zone each side (slide-not-lift). Laundry BPC: appliances on risers at 380–430mm. Kitchen FDR: U/L-shape layout with bracing surfaces. All are energy-conservation specifications for different rooms. The unmade connection: ALL residential task surfaces (kitchen worktop, laundry counter, bathroom vanity, bedroom dressing surface) should follow a unified specification: height 760–900mm adjustable, ≥400mm clear surface each side of activity centre, knee clearance ≥685mm × ≥600mm. Consistency across rooms serves DEM (predictable height reduces confusion), IntD (single learned height), OFS/PAIN (uniform energy-conserving height).',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0151','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas','Only ~10% of clients request inclusive design beyond code minimum (Zallio & Clarkson 2023). A-16 sensory rooms require 1:1 adult-child interaction with child in control of equipment matched to individual sensory profile (Unwin 2022/2024) — an OT-mediated specification no architect can implement from a drawing. Part 9 addresses OT as a design-stage consultant; no specification addresses OT at RFO (Ready for Occupancy) — commissioning the environment for the first occupant. For Tier 1/2 items (A-16, H-02, I-04, all adjustable items), an OT is required at that stage.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0152','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'entrances-and-circulation','PAS 6463 private individual retreat model does not transfer to collectivist cultures. Three adaptation pathways proposed (family-accompanied, unlabelled multipurpose, outdoor retreat) — none research-validated. The limitation extends beyond A-16: the guidebook''s entire environmental refuge concept (CON-0019), individual environmental control (H-02), and wayfinding labelling (D-02 pictograms) assume individual autonomy of use — a culturally specific assumption.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0153','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','CON-0141 requires visual alerting in acoustically isolated A-16 for DEAF. The seizure-safety BPC identifies VAD flash rates as seizure risk for NEU. Three-way interaction in A-16: NDV/AUT needs acoustic isolation → DEAF needs visual alerting → NEU needs flash protection. Resolution: K-04 vibrotactile wearable as primary (serves DEAF/DBL without visual or acoustic trigger); VAD at 0.5 Hz synchronised as supplementary; voice alarm at emergency-only volume with 5-second visual pre-alert; no unsynchronised strobes.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0154','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'kitchens-and-workspaces','Floor type is the single largest determinant of WBV in wheelchair users (Larivière 2024). Hard tile (common in kitchens/laundries) transmits maximum WBV. Wheelchair users spend extended time in one position during meal prep/laundry. Water-resistant resilient flooring (sheet vinyl with foam backing, sealed rubber) satisfies both water resistance AND WBV reduction. Hard tile is the worst material and should be flagged. VIS compatibility: plain colour, low pattern (per CON-0069).',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0155','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','Circadian lighting requires ≥250 melanopic EDI daytime (DEM: reduced agitation). A-16 sensory room needs calming function during daytime use — low melanopic EDI (≤10, warm CCT ≤2700K). If A-16 is on the building''s circadian lighting programme, a mid-morning user receives ≥250 melanopic EDI that contradicts the room''s calming function. A-16 lighting must be INDEPENDENT from the building circadian system.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0156','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','The failure taxonomy documents five failure modes. CS-02 (Gallaudet rounded corners) is the only documented case of a cross-population conflict identified post-occupancy and corrected. The nine conflict resolutions in cross-population-conflict-resolutions are individually evidence-supported, but the resolution framework as a composed system is untested. Only one resolution (DEAF/MOB sightline — CS-02) has been built and evaluated. The framework''s assumption that resolutions can be composed (applied simultaneously) is unvalidated. Gallaudet demonstrates that composition can fail.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0157','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','DAR BPC: retrofit cost multipliers ×5 to ×75+. Visitability BPC: $100–600 at construction for three core requirements. These are complementary but unlinked. Composite DAR cost-benefit envelope: construction = visitability + full DAR register ≈ $1,000–3,000. Retrofit without DAR ≈ $15,000–75,000+. Cost-benefit ratio ≈ 1:15 to 1:25. No existing BPC calculates this composite.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0158','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','Three populations — VIS, PAIN/OFS, UPL — have ZERO built-environment case study evidence globally AND no validated design framework (confirmed by case-studies BPC and design-framework BPC). These are the most vulnerable to "compliance without adequacy" failures because no outcome data demonstrates that code-compliant buildings actually serve them. CON-0140 previously identified UPL/OFS as most under-researched; this connection adds VIS and elevates the finding to a structural evidence gap.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0159','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','The guidebook uses three frameworks simultaneously without stating their relationship: ICF (classification), Competence-Press (person-environment interaction), Kawa (framing language). Additionally, for OFS/PAIN, the guidebook IS the first design framework — no external framework exists. This should be disclosed: the guidebook is creating, not applying, a design framework for these populations.',NULL,0,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0160','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','"Post-occupancy regression" is a documented failure mode (failure BPC): buildings start compliant, maintenance degrades access. DAR provisions are also vulnerable to regression — blocking zones invisible behind wall lining can be destroyed during renovation. DAR BPC specifies construction-stage verification but not operational-stage protection. Needed: nail plates over blocking, conduit labelling, O&M drawing notation as "DAR do not disturb" zones.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0161','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','NHS CAMHS is the "paradigm cross-population design failure case" (case-studies BPC): inpatient mental health environments systematically worsen outcomes for autistic young people. CON-0131 identified that CON-0002 incorrectly collapsed MH de-escalation room into A-16. NHS CAMHS IS the built consequence of that collapse. This elevates CON-0131 from "expert-identified correction" to "empirically documented failure avoidance."',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0162','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'kitchens-and-workspaces','All government adaptation programmes fund retrofit exclusively — no programme funds design-stage construction. UK DFG spends £711m/year on retrofits averaging £12,000–15,000/dwelling. If those dwellings had been built accessibly, the cost would have been ~£2,000–4,000/dwelling (1% of median build cost). The grant budget would fund 3–7× more accessible homes if spent at construction. This policy misallocation is the strongest policy argument in the guidebook but is not calculated in any BPC.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0163','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','Three data points create cost-per-outcome figures: (1) toilet visibility: $0 additional / 47% incontinence reduction (Marquardt 2011). (2) CAPABLE: $700–$1,400 modification / hospitalisation halved. (3) Loop floor plan: $0 / 94% vs 34% wayfinding. These are more compelling than cost-as-percentage. Practitioners respond to "$0 prevents 47% of incontinence events" more than "0.94% premium."',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0164','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','Jurisdiction matrix confirms: "No jurisdiction addresses DEM, NDV, or OFS in building code" across all 24 surveyed jurisdictions. Design-framework BPC confirms no validated framework for OFS/PAIN. The three fastest-growing disability categories in ageing populations are entirely absent from all building codes globally. This defines the guidebook''s primary value proposition: filling a documented regulatory vacuum.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0165','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'entrances-and-circulation','"Cost premium approaches zero after three experienced accessible-design projects" (Ielegems & Vanrie 2024). This is a learning-curve finding: the 0.94–3.92% figures include first-time teams. Experienced teams approach zero. Procurement of experienced accessible-design teams is itself an economic intervention.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0166','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','"Accessibility provisions specified as independent line items are disproportionately vulnerable to value engineering." Each item code in Part 4 is independent — a VE can remove B-10 while keeping A-10, destroying the multi-channel alerting system (CON-0042). Part 4 should define "integrated specification clusters" that must not be separated: hearing loop + acoustic ceiling + VAD; sensory zone system (B-01 + B-06 + F-01 + F-07); grab bar + hoist blocking + turning space.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0167','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','"Quality of support provided in the home is a greater determinant of tenant quality of life than the built environment" (Douglas et al. 2024, Tier 1). Ainsworth 2022: "Outcomes are co-produced by environment AND OT process quality." The guidebook''s physical specifications (Parts 4–8) are necessary but not sufficient. Without structured OT assessment, transition planning, and ongoing support, built environment specification alone does not produce accessibility outcomes.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0168','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','Seven provisions have stronger evidence in non-English literature: toilet visibility (DE), heat shock (JA), dementia village wayfinding (NL), fall threshold (JA), cost premium (BE/NL), ramp gradient (SE), loop garden (DA). For these, the non-English source is primary evidence. Part 1 should cite this as validation of the multilingual methodology. Part 4 should cite non-English primary sources FIRST.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0169','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','GC6 (2018) grounds the guidebook in equality (Art. 5), not only accessibility (Art. 9). Inaccessible new buildings are discriminatory from day one under Art. 5 — this duty is immediate, not progressive. Art. 9 for existing buildings is progressive. Part 1 should reference Art. 5 + GC6 as the stronger legal basis for new construction specifications.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0170','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','Malmgren Fänge 2019 reports OR 9.50 for wheelchair use at home with standardised OT assessment (SE/NO, Tier 1). Strongest single residential outcome effect size in the corpus — larger than CAPABLE (OR 3.95), Sheffield (39%), Faerden (d=2.0 is MH, not residential). This should anchor ALL wheelchair-accessible home specifications in Part 6.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0171','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','NHS CAMHS is the paradigm cross-population design failure: inpatient MH environments systematically worsen outcomes for autistic young people. This IS the built consequence of collapsing NDV/MH and NDV/AUT spatial provisions (CON-0131 correction). Elevates CON-0131 from expert judgment to documented-failure evidence.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0172','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','All government programmes fund retrofit only; none funds design-stage construction. UK DFG £711m/year on retrofits. If dwellings had been built accessibly, the cost would have been dramatically lower. The grant budget would fund substantially more accessible homes if redirected to construction.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0173','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','Three data points create cost-per-outcome figures: (1) toilet visibility: $0 additional / 47% incontinence reduction. (2) CAPABLE: $700–$1,400 / hospitalisation halved. (3) Loop floor plan: $0 / 94% vs 34% wayfinding. More compelling than cost-as-percentage.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0174','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','"No jurisdiction addresses DEM, NDV, or OFS in building code" across all 24 surveyed jurisdictions. The guidebook fills a documented regulatory vacuum.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0175','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','"Cost premium approaches zero after three experienced accessible-design projects" (Ielegems & Vanrie 2024). Procurement of experienced teams is itself an economic intervention.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0176','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','Accessibility provisions as independent line items are disproportionately vulnerable to value engineering. Part 4 should define "integrated specification clusters" — groups that must not be VE''d independently (hearing loop + acoustic ceiling + VAD; sensory zone system; grab bar + hoist blocking + turning space).',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0177','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','"Quality of support provided in the home is a greater determinant of tenant quality of life than the built environment" (Douglas 2024, Tier 1). Built environment specification is necessary but not sufficient. Part 1 must state this. Part 5 must include multicomponent intervention model.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0178','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','Seven provisions have stronger evidence in non-English literature. Part 1 should cite as validation of multilingual methodology. Part 4 should cite non-English primary sources first for these seven provisions.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0179','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'frameworks-and-methodology','CRPD Art. 5 + GC6 (2018) makes inaccessibility a form of disability-based discrimination — immediate duty, not progressive. Stronger legal basis than Art. 9 alone for new construction.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0180','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'population-general','Malmgren Fänge 2019 OR 9.50 for wheelchair use at home with standardised OT protocol (SE/NO, Tier 1). Strongest single residential effect size in corpus. Should anchor all wheelchair-accessible home specifications.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0114','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'health-and-symptom-management','A person suspended in a ceiling hoist (I-04) cannot reach a wall-mounted nurse call button (H-05). For DBL users, auditory call confirmation is also inaccessible. For high-level SCI users (C4+), hand-operated call buttons are inaccessible during the transfer itself. The hoist-to-bed/chair transfer is the highest-risk moment for falls and injury — and the moment when emergency communication is least available. No current specification addresses emergency communication during hoist operation.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0115','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','DBL and DEM rely on identical environmental mechanism — spatial predictability — through different sensory channels. DBL navigates by tactile memory of fixed spatial relationships; any furniture rearrangement breaks the tactile map. DEM navigates by cognitive spatial mapping; any layout change breaks the memory trace. The specification (D-09: consistent furniture arrangement) already serves both, and CON-0053 extends D-09 to VIS/DBL/IntD. But the *convergence mechanism* between DBL and DEM is undocumented: both populations are catastrophically (not merely inconvenienced) affected by spatial change. This elevates D-09 from "helpful consistency" to "safety-critical spatial stability" for the DBL+DEM co-occurrence — which occurs in aged-care settings where DEM prevalence is high and DBL (acquired) is co-occurring.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0116','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','Doors are the primary decision points in wayfinding. E-01 specifies door hardware (handle type, clear width, closing force) but not door-as-wayfinding-element. D-02 specifies wayfinding systems (signage, TWSI, landmarks) but not door-level cues. The gap: a person navigating a corridor encounters doors as the most salient spatial feature, but no specification links the door to the wayfinding system. DEM users identify rooms by door colour/position (Marquardt 2011). VIS users identify doors by contrast and tactile cue. IntD users need pictogram + door-colour coding. NDV/AUT users need consistent door-colour-to-function mapping (e.g., all toilet doors same colour). Currently, door appearance is an interior design decision with no specification guidance.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0117','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'health-and-symptom-management','Rest provision scales through three tiers — seated rest (I-03, every 50m on primary routes), enclosed low-stimulation space (D-05, one per floor), full sensory room (A-16, one per building) — but the scaling relationship is not specified. A practitioner does not know: (a) at what building occupancy does each tier become mandatory? (b) what is the distance/time threshold between tiers? (c) can D-05 substitute for A-16 in smaller buildings? These three items are specified independently. The scaling hierarchy is implicit in the BPC evidence (PAS 6463 recommends quiet spaces at building scale; OFS BPC specifies rest points at 50m intervals) but never codified.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0118','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'controls-and-hardware','H-01 (reach range) and H-02 (individual environmental control) specify controls for MOB, VIS, DEAF — but not DBL. DBL users cannot use: visual displays (temperature readouts, lighting level indicators), auditory feedback (beeps, click sounds), touchscreen interfaces, or any control that requires simultaneous visual + auditory confirmation. DBL needs: tactile-only operable controls with distinct raised profiles per function, haptic confirmation of state change (vibration pattern), Braille labels at consistent positions, and controls that remain legible when hands are wet (bathroom/kitchen context).',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0119','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'communication-and-alerts','CON-0040 specifies a three-zone sensory environment system (Zone 1 high activation → Zone 3 low activation) with lighting parameters per zone. F-07 specifies thermal zones (18–22°C range by population). These two zoning systems operate on the same building but are specified independently. The unmade coordination: Zone 3 (low activation) should be both dimmer/warmer CCT AND cooler temperature (for NEU/MS/OFS). Zone 1 (high activation) should be brighter/cooler CCT AND can tolerate wider thermal range. If lighting zones and thermal zones are designed by different consultants (typical), they may produce contradictory sensory environments — a Zone 3 space with high-activation lighting, or a Zone 1 space with low-activation thermal setpoint.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0120','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas','Grab bars serve DBL through a dual mechanism not captured in the current specification: (1) postural support (same as MOB/PAIN/OFS — CON-0003), and (2) haptic spatial landmark. For a deafblind person in a bathroom, the grab bar layout communicates the room''s topology — horizontal bar = wall alongside; L-shaped bar = corner; vertical bar = doorway/transfer point. This haptic wayfinding function means grab bar placement for DBL populations carries additional spatial-orientation requirements beyond the biomechanical positioning optimised for MOB. A grab bar placed at the biomechanically optimal height for sit-to-stand (CON-0003) may not be at the haptic-scan height for a standing DBL user.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0121','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'sensory-environment','CON-0006/CON-0059 identify circadian lighting (≥250 melanopic EDI daytime, 4000K+ CCT) as multi-population provision for DEM/NEU/MH/OFS. VIS is absent from the population coding despite two interactions: (1) Synergy — higher illuminance improves both circadian entrainment and visual acuity; many VIS conditions benefit from increased light levels that circadian targets independently require. (2) Potential conflict — some VIS conditions (photophobia in albinism, certain macular conditions) are aggravated by high-intensity light; circadian targets may exceed comfortable levels for these sub-populations. The interaction is bidirectional and undocumented.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0122','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','DEAF corridor width (2440mm for signing conversation, DeafSpace 2010) subsumes MOB corridor width (1800mm turning, IDeA Center). In any building serving DEAF populations, the DEAF signing-width specification automatically satisfies the MOB turning-space requirement. This is a *subsumption connection* — the higher specification contains the lower. No conflict exists, but the cost and space implication is significant and undocumented: a designer who specifies for DEAF first (2440mm) does not need a separate MOB corridor width specification. Conversely, a designer who specifies for MOB only (1800mm) creates inadequate signing space for DEAF users.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0123','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','IntD and DEM wayfinding specifications converge more completely than any other population pair in the guidebook. CON-0001 identified the circulation geometry overlap (loop/linear, no dead-ends). The full convergence extends to the entire wayfinding system:
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0124','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas','UPL BPC documents that optimal grab bar grasp location varies with body height (r=0.67, Levine 2025) — fixed placement cannot serve all users. CON-0120 (this session) proposes grab bars as haptic spatial landmarks for DBL. These two findings interact: if grab bar height is variable (UPL Tier 2 provision), then DBL users cannot rely on consistent haptic landmarks for spatial orientation.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0125','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','NEU BPC Opus synthesis establishes bilateral redundancy as the Tier 1 provision for hemispatial neglect: environmental cues on BOTH sides of corridors, because unilateral neglect makes one side invisible. VIS BPC specifies signage at eye level on both sides of corridors for legibility from either approach direction. Both populations independently require bilateral environmental cues — NEU for neglect compensation, VIS for approach-direction legibility.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0126','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'health-and-symptom-management','OFS BPC specifies rest seating every 25-30m on primary routes (tightened from BS 8300''s 50m for MOB). VIS BPC specifies continuous TWSI on primary routes with attention indicators at decision points (ISO 23599). These specifications occupy the same physical space — the primary circulation route — but are specified independently.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0127','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','Three-way interaction on wall colour/finish:
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0128','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas','MOB BPC specifies 1800mm turning circle in bathrooms. DBL BPC specifies intervenor clear floor space ≥900×1500mm at service counters (GAP-NEW-01). In a residential bathroom, a DBL user with an intervenor needs BOTH MOB turning space AND intervenor standing space simultaneously — the intervenor stands alongside the DBL user during transfers and orientation.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0129','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas','PAIN BPC specifies storage at 750-1050mm throughout — the zone between hip and shoulder that avoids bending or overhead reaching. IntD BPC does not specify storage height, but IntD users benefit from predictable, visible, consistent storage heights — not because of physical limitation but because finding items in unpredictable locations increases cognitive load and triggers frustration/distress.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0130','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'wayfinding-and-signage','DEM BPC specifies toilet visible from primary occupied space (CON-0018, Marquardt 2011 — reduces incontinence). IntD BPC specifies reception/assistance point within sight of entrance (CSA B651 §4.7). OFS BPC specifies rest seating within 25-30m of any point.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0131','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','**CON-0002 correction required.** CON-0002 (CONSUMED) proposes collapsing the MH de-escalation room into A-16, retiring the separate MH room concept. The MH BPC Opus synthesis (completed 2026-03-30, AFTER CON-0002 was applied) explicitly contradicts this: "These serve different clinical functions and cannot be combined. A single ''quiet room'' fails MH users (who need exit sightline and staff-accessible de-escalation) and NDV users (who need acoustic isolation without staff presence)."
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0132','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'communication-and-alerts','Biophilic design provisions (BIO-series: indoor planting, nature views, natural materials) are therapeutic for DEM (reduced agitation — Al Khatib 2024 SR), NDV/MH (stress reduction — Ulrich), and NEU (ART/SRT restorative benefit). The air quality BPC specifies for OFS/MCAS spaces: "low-VOC, low-pollen species only; no strongly scented flowering plants." Additionally, F-06 (Fragrance-Free Policy) prohibits fragrance diffusers including any HVAC-integrated scent system.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0133','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'entrances-and-circulation','H-01/H-02 specify controls for MOB/UPL: reach range (400-1100mm), activation force (≤22.2N), lever hardware, no pinch/grip/twist. The controls BPC is entirely physical-access focused. Three populations have cognitive operability requirements undocumented in the controls specification:
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0134','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'controls-and-hardware','Faerden 2022 reports Cohen''s d = 2.0 for patient support and d = 1.7 for staff support when sensory modulation rooms are available in psychiatric inpatient settings. This is the largest single effect size for any built-environment intervention in the entire BPC corpus — larger than Clemson 2023 (fall prevention, 38% reduction), larger than CAPABLE (hospitalisation 0.43→0.23/year), larger than Sheffield (39% care hour reduction).
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0135','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','The deaf-acoustic BPC specifies Auracast (Bluetooth LE Audio) infrastructure as a DAR provision in all new assembly spaces, alongside IEC 60118-4 hearing loop systems. IEC 60118-17 (Auracast standard) is expected late 2027. During the transition period, dual provision (loop + Auracast-ready infrastructure) is best practice.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0136','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'entrances-and-circulation','Door force specification (≤30N preferred, ≤38N maximum) is coded for MOB (wheelchair user arm strength). OFS and PAIN are not coded despite clear clinical rationale: OFS energy conservation — every door push depletes the post-exertional malaise budget; cumulative door-opening through a building visit can trigger PEM. PAIN — joint loading on hands, wrists, and shoulders during manual door operation aggravates arthritic and fibromyalgia pain.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0137','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','The MH BPC documents that exceeding bed capacity in psychiatric wards produces OR 5.36 for aggression (Weltens 2023, experience sampling method). This is a built-environment capacity specification: the number of beds per ward is a design parameter with a direct, large, quantified effect on safety outcomes. The OR is among the largest in the MH BPC evidence base — comparable to the absence of private space (van der Schaaf 2013).
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0138','CONSUMED','MODERATE',NULL,'sensory-environment','CON-0039 proposes RT60 ≤0.3 s as Universal Mode universal for speech-critical rooms, based on DEAF evidence (Iglehart 2020). The room-acoustic-performance BPC documents that NDV/AUT evidence (Bettarello 2021, Caniato 2024) indicates existing standards (calibrated to neurotypical populations) are insufficient and that autistic users are "significantly more affected by modest background noise increases (52→55 dBA)." The BPC suggests sub-0.3s RT60 may be needed for NDV/AUT but no quantified target exists.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0139','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','HIGH',NULL,'cross-cutting','Phase 1A §7.4 states the ● / ○ system does not further stratify within ●. But the MH BPC contains Faerden 2022 (d=2.0), CAPABLE (RCT, hospitalisation halved), and Clemson Cochrane (38% fall reduction) — all ●, but the effect sizes differ by an order of magnitude. Part 1 should cite the d=2.0 as the upper anchor of ● evidence, demonstrating the range within the marker. This strengthens the methodology transparency commitment (Phase 1A §10.2) without changing the ● / ○ system.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0140','CONSUMED','MODERATE',NULL,'health-and-symptom-management','UPL BPC: "zero PubMed-indexed studies on one-handed kitchen/bathroom built-environment design." OFS BPC: all specifications extrapolated from clinical evidence, zero OFS-specific architectural standards in any jurisdiction. These two populations share a meta-characteristic: they are the most under-researched populations with the largest specification-to-evidence gaps. CON-0045 documents VIS/PAIN/OFS case study absence. UPL should be added to that finding — UPL has zero case studies AND zero primary design research.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0141','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','A-16 specifies acoustic isolation (STC ≥50, RT60 ≤0.3s, NC ≤25). This creates a communication isolation hazard for DEAF users — a sound-isolated room without visual alerting or transparent sightlines prevents a DEAF user inside from receiving emergency alerts or communicating with people outside. Project-standards already flags this for D-05 (CON-0036: "sound attenuation creates emergency egress and communication isolation risk for DEAF"). The same logic applies to A-16 but is undocumented.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0142','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'communication-and-alerts','Project-standards specifies 18–22°C working target for thermoregulation-impaired populations, with mechanical cooling as medically necessary in hot-humid tropical contexts. F-04 air quality specifies ≥15 L/s fresh air per person for OFS/MCAS spaces with no recirculated air without HEPA. In tropical contexts, these two specifications interact adversely: high fresh-air supply rates at 32°C+ ambient increase cooling load dramatically. The HVAC system must simultaneously cool to ≤22°C AND supply ≥15 L/s fresh air AND filter to MERV 13+ — this is an engineering coordination constraint that neither F-04 nor F-07 documents.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0143','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'bathrooms-and-wet-areas','MOB BPC: ADA 1524mm turning circle rejected; 1800mm best practice; CSA B651 2100mm for 95th-percentile power chairs. DEM BPC: toilet visible from bedroom doorway; loop circulation; no dead-ends. In residential care where MOB+DEM co-occur (the most common co-occurrence in aged care), the turning circle and the toilet-sightline specifications interact: a 1800mm turning circle placed in a bathroom may block the toilet-sightline from the bedroom door if the door swing and turning space are not coordinated. The spatial layout must simultaneously satisfy: DEM sightline (visual axis from bedroom door to toilet), MOB turning (1800mm inscribed circle), and door swing (clear opening 900mm without intruding into turning space).',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0144','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','The sensory-relief BPC notes: "Rashid et al. (2025) taxonomy identifies that most frameworks overemphasise interior elements relative to spatial configuration (adjacency, sequencing, approach). This is a gap in A-16''s current specification scope." CON-0023 (CONSUMED) independently flags the same finding from Al-Harasis 2025: "current autism design frameworks rely on intuition sensory zoning as the main driver for spatial topology without quantifying the sensory drivers."
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0145','CONSUMED','MODERATE',NULL,'sensory-environment','Hearing loop field uniformity (±3 dB per IEC 60118-4) requires specific spatial conditions: metal structures, underfloor heating, and electrical wiring interfere with magnetic field. H-04 (digital infrastructure) specifies conduit routing but does not cross-reference hearing loop installation constraints. When H-04 conduit and A-10 hearing loop are designed independently, the conduit routing may degrade loop performance.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0146','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'sensory-environment','DEAF BPC: ≥300 lux diffuse, matte-reflected, shadow-free lighting in communication zones; backlighting eliminated; lighting serves sign language visibility. VIS BPC: ≥300 lux in circulation without glare; no sudden illuminance transitions >5:1. These targets are identical in value (≥300 lux) and complementary in character (both require diffuse, glare-free light). But the rationale is different: DEAF needs light on the signer''s face and hands; VIS needs light on environmental surfaces for legibility.
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0147','CONSUMED-DEFERRED','MODERATE',NULL,'cross-cutting','IntD BPC: "reception/assistance point within sight of entrance" (CSA B651 §4.7). OFS BPC: "rest seating within 25–30m." In a healthcare or education building serving both populations, the entrance sequence must provide BOTH: visible assistance AND immediate rest. These are complementary, not competing: a reception desk with adjacent seated waiting serves both requirements simultaneously. But no specification links them.',NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
INSERT INTO "connections" VALUES('CON-0181','CONSUMED','HIGH',NULL,'entrances-and-circulation',NULL,NULL,1,NULL,'2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration','2026-05-08 21:00','session_2026-05-08-c1-migration');
