German DIN EN 15251 indoor climate. ASR A3.5 workplace temperature. No care-home specific standard.

CROSS-JURISDICTIONAL SYNTHESIS:
- PMC7557728 (2020): Dementia residents in lower air temps, MORE rated "cool/cold." "Symptomless cooling" risk.
- ScienceDirect 2023 literature review: PMV-PPD index has "limitations for elderly." Models based on young adults.
- PMC12609229 (2025 SR): Older adults: reduced sweating, altered thermal perception, increased mortality risk.
- Thermoneutral zone 23–27°C for clothed adults, BUT elderly show thermoregulatory extremes even within this range.
- Optimum temperature elderly = 21.1°C wearing 1 clo (same as young adults when clothing controlled).
ADVERSARIAL:
- Standard comfort models (PMV-PPD per ISO 7730) NOT validated for elderly populations.
- "Multi-node thermoregulation models are inadequately studied" for elderly.
- Dementia patients may not perceive cold AND cannot communicate discomfort.
- Energy cost of higher heating in care homes acknowledged but not quantified in evidence base.
- Griggs 2019 (GAP-260) was exercise physiology, not built environment — reopened per adversarial protocol.
- No specific building code temperature standard for care homes exists beyond general HVAC guidance.
PROTOCOL COMPLIANCE: FULL — cross-jurisdictional synthesis, protocol fields populated.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-10T21:34:02Z','session_2026-05-10e-slug3-adversarial');

