STANDARD: Japan has a comprehensive REGULATORY+INCENTIVE framework under バリアフリー法 (Barrier-Free Law, 2006) — but published cost-impact research is sparse.

Framework that affects construction economics:
- 建築物移動等円滑化基準 (mandatory baseline standard, 義務基準) — minimum legally required
- 建築物移動等円滑化誘導基準 (guidance standard, 誘導基準) — voluntary but rewarded
- 建築設計標準 (Building Design Standard, MLIT) — guidance document with detailed implementation
- 2024-06-21 公布 / 2025-06-01 施行: major revision affecting toilets, parking, theatre seating

INCENTIVE STRUCTURE (not in BPC):
- 容積率特例 (FAR/floor area ratio bonus) for buildings meeting 誘導基準
- 固定資産税 reduction (fixed asset tax) for accessibility renovations
- 都市計画税 reduction (urban planning tax) for accessibility renovations
- 所得税/法人税 accelerated depreciation (割増償却) for ≥2000m² certified buildings
- バリアフリー環境整備促進事業: subsidies for movement systems, toilets, elevators in publicly-significant buildings

ADVERSARIAL: MLIT''s own 2018 cost analysis (バリアフリー化に係る費用負担のあり方について) explicitly states for railways: "投資コストが大きく、収益に繫がりづらい" (investment cost is large, hard to translate into revenue). This contradicts the cross-jurisdictional consensus that barrier-free is "marginal cost." For Japanese transit infrastructure specifically, MLIT acknowledges substantial cost burden — but no quantitative percentage published.

CORRECTION: Prior batch note said "MLIT data exists but not independently published as research." This understated the situation. MLIT HAS published documents discussing cost burden; what''s missing is INDEPENDENT academic analysis. The MLIT documents acknowledge non-trivial cost in some contexts (transit) while Japanese MLIT-funded studies for buildings emphasize the incentive structure as offset.','2026-05-09 05:35','session_2026-05-09-search-coverage','2026-05-11 01:27','session_2026-05-10f-term-alias-expansion');

